At the bottom was a circular room filled with ornate carpets and lounge pillows, small tables with wine and dates, tapestries on the walls with complex colors that defied definition in the shadowy haze of the place, in which also drifted lazy insense smoke. It was the torches along the walls that emitted the watery hue, giving the space a close and undersea aura.<br>
In the midst of this was a man standing, with one foot propped on a couch, playing the baliset with his eyes closed. His clothing was simple, dark and loose, yet of rich materials. It seemed as if he didn't notice her entrance to the room as he kept playing on... but then he stopped and turned to her with casual regard.<br>
&quot;Hello, young lady! I thought to be alone tonight... and so you've heard a song that no one else has heard in a very long time...&quot; He smiled &quot;Come, my dear, never am I so consumed with memories that I will pass on an evening in the gracious company of a beautiful lady such as thee... will you not chance this poor wine and paltry table of modest fare? I crave to hear your tale... and any others you have heard which bring a smile to your lips!&quot; <br>
He was an older gentleman, vibrant looking and handsome still, with penetrating hazel eyes that were never invasive. Gaelim told him many of her favorite stories, including her own, and was finally prompted after some wine to sing, which so delighted him that he picked up the tempo and fashioned a jig to it and danced merrily around the room! Then he told some of his own tale, about a time spent on ships as the bard of a group of philosophical pirates, of the strange places they went and the perils that sometimes claimed the lives of friends. These memories made his eyes grow wistful so Gaelim then prodded him the sing for her, which he complied with a small epic, full of love and pride, passion and vanity, death and wonder. Gaelim became lost in the river of his song as it flowed forth... his voice was the poetry of elemental vitality... she felt like she was made of bubbling light.<br>
After this performance, as he closed his eyes and sighed deeply, she walked over to him and kissed him on his lips, which startled him.<br>
Then Gaelim heard footsteps from the stairs and turned to see Liani come into the room. &lt;laughing happily and bounding over to Liani in her bearfur underclothes&gt;<br>
&quot;Oh, High Lady! I've just met your distinguished other guest here... mister... ah... &quot; Frowning she turns toward the gentleman she has been having such a merry time with... &quot;You know, I never did get you na...&quot;<br>
He was gone. Everything in the room was gone, replaced with cold stone floors and cobwebs stretched in the corners and over a few old boxes and trunks, hinges rusted. The abrupt change, as well as Liani staring at her, caused a wave of dizziness to fizzle through Gaelim's head and she had to crouch down on the floor. &lt;I can still smell him... my fingers and toes are still tingling from his song... what happened here?&gt;<br>
As Gaelim stood back up unsteadily, she noticed a particular shape in the corner, covered in dust and cobwebs... an instrument case. Pulled to it, she tries to open it, instead the lid rips off in mouldering decay... inside is an beautiful ancient baliset, precious woods cracked and discolored with age, though smouldering even still with a palpible psychic residue of ages past and glories remembered in spirit alone.<br>
&quot;Gosh...&quot; murmurs Gaelim as she brings the baliset over to Liani, her eyes wide with awe and shock and bewilderment... <br>
and eventually, a wistful smile.<br>
